        "# MAGIS-100 NDK Dephasing Forecast Generator\n",
        "\n",
        "**Author:** Eric C. Thompson  \n",
        "**Related Publication:** [Zenodo DOI](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19389059)\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook generates a closure-informed forecast for momentum-quadratic residual dephasing in a MAGIS-100-like atom interferometer using the Null-Directional Kinematics (NDK) fixed-cell transport model.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Overview\n",
        "In the NDK framework, space is modeled through a fixed-cell transport picture with finite informational capacity. When a large-momentum-transfer (LMT) atom interferometer drives atomic wavepackets to large separations, the model predicts an additional residual dephasing burden associated with transport across that finite substrate.\n",
        "\n",
        "The forecast produced here has three main features:\n",
        "- it scales quadratically with the LMT order $n$,\n",
        "- it grows linearly with interrogation time $T$,\n",
        "- and, under the thermal coherence identification used in the related note, it increases linearly with source temperature $\\Theta$.\n",
        "\n",
        "## How to Read the Plot\n",
        "- **Solid lines:** median predicted residual dephasing for representative source temperatures of 50 pK, 100 pK, and 200 pK.\n",
        "- **Shaded bands:** model-side coherence-parameter sensitivity range from the sweep over the remaining coherence-transfer quantities $w_{\\rm coh}$ and $\\lambda_{\\rm coh,0}$. These are not experimental error bars.\n",
        "- **Black threshold lines:** approximate 0.1% and 1.0% contrast-loss benchmarks.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Experimental Usage\n",
        "Experimental users can modify:\n",
        "- `T_fixed` to match a different interrogation time,\n",
        "- the temperature values to explore alternate source-preparation conditions,\n",
        "- and the coherence-parameter arrays to test different preparation-side assumptions.\n",
        "\n",
        "The main purpose of the notebook is not to provide a single fixed magnitude prediction, but to visualize the shape of the predicted residual scaling law and its dependence on experimentally controllable parameters.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Theoretical Foundation & Reference Papers\n",
        "The equations and geometric constants used in this simulation are derived from the Null-Directional Kinematics (NDK) framework. For the full mathematical derivations of the underlying theory, the transport model, and the primitive vacuum cell geometry, please refer to the following foundational papers:\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Core NDK Framework:** Thompson, E. C. (2026). *Null-Directional Kinematics and the Statistical Structure of Spacetime: Clock Functionals, Transport Geometry, and Directional Support* (Version v6). Zenodo. [https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18665370](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18665370)\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Primary LMT Dephasing Model:** Thompson, E. C. (2026). *Macroscopic Dephasing in LMT Atom Interferometry from a Fixed-Cell Transport Model: A Short Letter on the NDK Momentum-Quadratic Contrast Floor* (Version v4). Zenodo. [https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19186680](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19186680)\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Vacuum Cell Geometry (closure-informed choice $\\eta=\\pi$):** Thompson, E. C. (2026). *A Conditional Closure Mechanism for G and $\\hbar$ in a Primitive NDK Horizon Cell Model*. Zenodo. [https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19375997](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19375997)"
      ],
